                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.011/6.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé d’Affaires</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 12, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In the Assembly yesterday the Minister for Foreign Affairs declined to comply
                    with the Assembly’s demand that he sign the constitution. A stormy scene ensued,
                    in which American intervention was attacked. The Assembly does nothing without
                    the assent of Mena, whose party is uniformly anti-American. To allay the
                    excitement the Minister for Foreign Affairs, at the request of President <pb
                        facs="1110" n="994" xml:id="pg_994"/> Díaz, agreed to sign. The President
                    and Mena have promised me, however, not to allow promulgation of the
                    constitution until January 31.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gunther.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
